This is the Readme file for SMPReaderUSB project and code. It uses Objective
Development's firmware-only USB driver for Atmel's(r) AVR(r) microcontrollers 
- V-USB. For more information please visit http://www.obdev.at/vusb/.

FILES
=====

  README .............. The file you are currently reading.
  /software ........... SMPReaderUSB sources for PC-based host.

  smpreaderusb.c ...... Main firmware code

  smpreaderusb.aws .... AVR Studio project file
  smpreaderusb.aps .... AVR Studio project file
  Makefile ............ for Project building through make
  make_config.h ....... External constants - only for F_CPU - clock definition
  requests.h  ......... USB request constant definitions
  usbconfig.h ......... Custom V-USB config, see comments inside code for
                        details
  usbdrv.c............. V-USB core, included into the SMPReaderUSB project
  usbdrv.h              -- / --
  usbdrvasm.asm         -- / --
  usbdrvasm.S           -- / --
  usbdrvasm12.inc       -- / --
  usbdrvasm128.inc      -- / --
  usbdrvasm15.inc       -- / --
  usbdrvasm16.inc       -- / --
  usbdrvasm165.inc      -- / --
  usbdrvasm18-crc.inc   -- / --
  usbdrvasm20.inc       -- / --
  usbportability.h      -- / --
  asmcommon.inc         -- / --
  oddebug.c ........... Debug macro
  oddebug.h ........... Debug macro



Each subdirectory contains a separate Readme file which explains its
contents.

PREREQUISITES
=============
SMPReaderUSB is written in C and assembler. You need either avr-gcc or IAR CC 
to compile the project. I recommend avr-gcc because it
is free and easily available. Gcc version 3 generates slightly more
efficient code than version 4. Not every release is tested with
the IAR compiler. 

Ready made avr-gcc tool chains are available for most operating systems:
  * Windows: WinAVR http://winavr.sourceforge.net/
  * Mac: CrossPack for AVR Development http://www.obdev.at/crosspack/
  * Linux and other Unixes: Most free Unixes have optional packages for AVR
    development. If not, follow the instructions at
    http://www.nongnu.org/avr-libc/user-manual/install_tools.html

Host side program are compiled with Microsoft Visual Studio C/C++ for Windows platform.

Project depend on libusb. Libusb is available from

http://libusb.sourceforge.net/ for Unix and
http://libusb-win32.sourceforge.net/ for Windows.

